      <hedline>
        <hl1>Access to Health Care</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Sen Paul Wellsteon and service employees union president Andrew L Stern endorses Health Security for All Americans Act (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A Sept. 24 editorial was correct to say we should use part of the budget surplus to ensure every American has quality health care -- and there is a bill before Congress to do just that.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A Sept. 24 editorial was correct to say we should use part of the budget surplus to ensure every American has quality health care -- and there is a bill before Congress to do just that.</p>
        <p>Over five years, the Health Security for All Americans Act would provide all Americans with access to the comprehensive coverage now enjoyed by members of Congress. It learns from the 1993 debate by building on what works now and fixing what does not.  States would decide how best to ensure access, with financing provided by companies, the federal government, the states -- and individuals, according to ability to pay.</p>
        <p>The bill is supported by the Service Employees International Union, the largest union of health care workers; no one has a greater stake in improving the system than nurses and other caregivers.</p>
        <p>PAUL WELLSTONE  ANDREW L. STERN  Washington, Sept. 26, 2000</p>
        <p>The writers are, respectively, a senator from Minnesota and the president of the Service Employees International Union.</p>
      </block>
